CHAPTER XV. Restraiuts respecting] Conquest.

I. Equity, which is required, and humanity, which is praised, towards individuals, are the more requisite and praiseworthy‚ towards nations and parts of nations, inasmuch as the injury or kindness is greater with the number. Now as other things may be acquired in a just war, so may imperial authority over a people, and the right which the people itself has in the government: but only so far as is limited, either by the nature of a penalty arising from delict, or by the nature of some other debt. To which is to be added, the reason of averting extreme danger. This last cause is commonly mixed up with others3 but is, in reality, to be much regarded for its own sake, both in establishing peace and in using victory.
